At the beginning of August, it was 52 percent.
Now six out of 10 Republicans are positive about Donald Trump.
About three out of 10 say they have a negative opinion.
And all of these things are prevalent in the early stages.
A Quinnipiac poll in Iowa last week found that 60 percent of Republicans there favor Trump.
Two-thirds of the GOP voters would have Trump as their candidate.
In a CNN/ORC poll conducted last week, 67 percent of Republicans said they would either "enjoy" or "satisfy" Trump's candidacy.
Only two in 10 say they would be "disappointed" if he ran.
Ben Carson alone generates about the same level of enthusiasm as Trump (43 percent say they would be "thrilled" versus 40 percent who say the same about Trump).
Next in line for admiration?
Marco Rubio, who only has 21%.
On the other hand, 47 percent of Republicans say they would be "displeased" or "disappointed" if the establishment's favorite Jeb Bush becomes the nominee.
Most Republicans don't see Trump's temper as a problem.
While Trump has been widely criticized for his bragging and insults, 52 percent of Republican-leaning voters nationwide think the tycoon has the right temperament to be president, an ABC News/Washington post poll showed Monday.
The same figure is coming out of the nation's first closed-door rally in Iowa, where the same 52 percent of Republicans think he's the man who could be commander-in-chief, according to Quinnipiac last week.
Still, 44 percent think he's not the man to be effective in office, and nearly six in 10 independent voters say his temperament is not right for the White House, according to ABC/Post.
Republican voters are getting used to the idea.
When they put on their smart hats, Republican voters think Trump is serious.
When asked who was the most likely to win the GOP nomination, four in 10 said Trump was the favorite, according to a CNN/ORC poll last week.
That's not the case anymore, with four of the 10 being put on Jeb Bush at the end of July.
Full disclosure: GOP voters never had the right magic crystal before.
At the same time, in the last cycle, four out of 10 Republicans picked Rick Perry as the most likely candidate, while only 28 percent backed Mitt Romney as a possible candidate.
Still, it shows that many GOP voters find Trump's campaign convincing.
Even if the Republicans were to rally around another candidate, Trump is still ahead of the game.
Some pundits suggest that this dispersion is likely to be to Trump's advantage, with those who don't support Trump evenly distributed among those who support more than a dozen other candidates.
