Metcash launches bottom-up campaign to counter Aldi's onslaught
Metcash is trying to protect its IGA stores from Aldi's onslaught in South Australia and Western Australia.
The wholesale food supplier has launched a grassroots campaign to protect the market share of IGA retailers in South Australia and Western Australia in light of the upcoming $700 million infusion by Aldi.
As Aldi prepares to open two wholesale warehouses and the first of 120 stores in South and Western Australia early next year, Metcash and IGA supermarkets are strengthening relationships with local food suppliers and promoting the IGA brand through marketing in the mainstream media and social media and at events such as the Adelaide Show.
The campaign is being joined by IGA retailers and suppliers, such as the ice cream maker Simmo's in Dunsborough, which offers tasting in IGA stores, and shop owners who sell tickets to regular customers at a discount for South Australian Football League matches.
Metcash is expected to reveal more details of its protection strategy on September 29, the day the food, beverage and consumer goods wholesale supplier holds its annual investor strategy day.
There is a lot of competition, as in South Australia and Western Australia, IGA-branded stores make up almost 30% of all Metcash stores and show higher profitability than the Metcash IGA network in the eastern states.
Shoppers in South and Western Australia are known to be more committed to their usual routes, so the market here is more favorable to IGA retailers than in the states of New South Wales, Victoria and Queensland - more than 30 percent in the South Australian and 24 percent in the WA compared to approximately 14 percent in the eastern states.
However, analysts such as Morgan Stanley believe that Aldi will capture 5 percent of the grocery market in these two states within 12 months of opening its first stores, taking sales from all the players present, but mainly from independent retailers.
In a report published this week, Tom Kirat, an analyst at Morgan Stanley, estimates that IGA retailers could lose $360 million in sales for the year, and Metcash $250 million by the end of 2016.
The forecast is based on the assumption that Aldi will open 25 stores in South Africa and 30 in WA next year, achieving sales of $500 million and $600 million in those markets respectively.
The loss of revenue and food sales volumes at Metcash's high fixed costs could cost the company about $13 million in earnings before interest and taxes, Mr. Kirat believes.
Meanwhile, Metcash is losing market share in the eastern states, mostly to Aldi and Coles, and that's despite a recent Morgan Survey finding that IGA has the most loyal customers.
Morgan Stanley estimates that Metcash grocery sales will fall 3.8 percent in 2016, 4.1 percent in 2017, and 2.1 percent in 2018, reducing the company's market share from 14 percent in 2015 to 10.3 percent by 2020.
Last week, leading fund manager Hamish Douglas, founder of Magellan Financial Group, remarked to attendees at a business lunch in Melbourne that Metcash "could very likely disappear within a decade.
Metcash declined to comment publicly on Mr. Douglas' comments.
But it's believed a member of the Metcash board contacted Mr. Douglas last week.
IGA's market share has decreased from 18 to 14 percent since 2010, and Metcash's food business revenues, which it supplies to some 1,200 IGA retailers, have fallen by 43 percent since 2012 due to operational deleveraging and pressure on sales and profitability.
