What happens when the Federal Reserve raises interest rates
If rates go up, the bull market will crash, bond yields will rise, and the economy will fall into recession.
We know that.
What we don't know is how long it'll take to attack, and how long it'll last.
For economics specifically, history explains little about time.
The recession came just 11 months after the first rate hike, and for 86 months.
The Federal Reserve's toughness in raising rates often, though not always, determines the response of the economy and financial assets.
That's why the Fed is so insistent that investors should focus not on when he's going to raise rates, but how long it will take to adjust.
In fact, there are many variables at play.
Eventually, however, market participants may find that all the fuss about raising rates is exaggerated.
"The first rate hike by the Federal Reserve with the onset of the global financial crisis will inevitably be interpreted by some as signaling the end of the 'cheap money' era", Julian Jessop, chief international economist at Capital Economics, said in a client comment.
Conversely, we do not expect that a gradual return of US interest rates to more normal but still low levels will be the seismic momentum that many fear.
That doesn't mean there won't be consequences, though.
Here's a look at how some sectors of the economy might have responded to historical trends:
As the market has seen over the last month or so, expecting a rate hike can lead to volatility for a while.
When the stakes are raised, however, the consequences are usually not so dramatic.
"It is unlikely that equity earnings will slow for 12 to 24 months after the first jump, which again likely reflects a delay in monetary policy", Deutsche Bank analysts said in a recent study of the Federal Reserve's rate hike.
More specifically, if the market has been more volatile over the last 35 years or so - about 14 percent - in the direction of higher rates, it stays fairly flat for 250 days after that (an average increase of 2.6 percent), then, after 500 days, it returns to normal with an average return of 14.4 percent over the last six cycles, according to a recent analysis conducted by Bob Doll, chief equity trading strategist at Nuveen Asset Management, published in Barron's.
Deutsche says that the result for securities tends not to become more pronounced at the rate hike stage, and earnings from shares begin to decline.
Recessions are a fact of economic life, but rising rates often play a role in contributing to them.
In this case, the Federal Reserve is being put in a situation that has never existed before and could accelerate a recession.
Basically, gross domestic product will be at almost its lowest point in the entire existence of the higher rate.
According to Deutsche Bank, in 118 cases of rate hikes since 1950, only twice the nominal annual GDP was below 4.5 percent.
Even though it was 3.6 percent in the second quarter of 2015, few believe it will last, with only 1.5 percent in the third quarter, according to the Atlanta Fed.
Raising rates in such a volatile economic environment could be risky and raises the question "will it be different this time", Deutsche reported.
Market participants have been preparing for the Federal Reserve's rate hike all year, with their eyes glued to the Federal Open Market Committee meeting that ends Thursday.
While many strategists and economists believe that the FOMC could have approved a rate hike at this meeting, futures trading only suggests a 25% probability.
"In our study, all the rate hikes from 1950 to the present day have been in a GDP-enhancing financial leverage supercycle, closing the peaks that preceded the recession very quickly after the recovery began", the report said.
By contrast, it was an extremely slow recovery from the worst recession in the selected period.
The current cycle is the longest the Federal Reserve has waited since the end of the last recession; a record 35 months, and it's been 74 months in total and it's not over yet.
Fixed income has also become volatile as the market expects interest rates to rise, and this scenario is somewhat similar to what is happening for stocks.
The fundamental difference is that bonds will be affected more quickly than stocks when the Federal Reserve changes its strategic course.
In the case of bonds, it seems that the yield vector changes immediately after the first rate hike/decrease in the cycle.
At the end of the rate hike cycle, bond yields immediately fall", reports Deutsche.
Strategists at Charles Schwab believe that higher rates will bring the yields of long-term and short-term bonds closer together, making the curve flatter.
High-yield bonds often do better in such a climate, though "we still fear yield fluctuations", says the study's author, Kathy Jones, a fixed-income analyst at Schwab.
Interestingly, Jones believes that markets have already adapted to the expected outcomes of the Federal system's policies.
"In addition to the strengthening of the dollar and the decline in inflation expectations, there are signs that the market has adjusted to the prospect of tighter monetary policy", she wrote.
Interest rates on short-term loans have risen, yield curves are flatter, credit spreads have expanded, volatility has increased - all characteristics of a market under the Federal System's tightening policy.
In general, companies with their main business in the US will benefit from higher interest rates and local products will become more attractive.
International companies with a lot of debt will be worse off, as a rising dollar makes their products more expensive in the global marketplace, and their debt more expensive in the financial marketplace.
