Daily life has become noticeably worse compared to January, when the situation was improving, and this affected most Greek citizens.
Evreunews: But you say that if you win the elections, you will seek alliances with other parties, including SYRIZA.
VANGELIS MAIMARAKIS: The thing is, as we've learned in the last few years, Greece cannot move forward without understanding and cooperation.
It is no coincidence that in all the other countries where rescue programmes have been or are still in operation, political forces and all the ruling parties have come together to implement the programme on which they have agreed, without renouncing their political or ideological autonomy.
That's why I firmly believe that at this stage, only the cooperation of political forces and institutions will allow the country to move forward.
Euronews: Your party voted in favour of an agreement between Mr. Tsipras and the country's creditors.
If you become the new Prime Minister on Monday, will you keep this agreement or will you try to change it, at least in part?
VANGELIS MAIMARAKIS: We actually voted to move Greece along the European path because we have a good idea of the disastrous consequences that leaving the EU would have.
Europe is helping us by subsidizing our farmers for their produce, we have solidarity funds, the Juncker package and assistance in the banking sector.
All of this would have been lost if there hadn't been a treaty with Europe.
But the current austerity measures are the result of how Mr. Tsipras negotiated.
I know Europe has no desire to destroy us.
Europe wants to help us.
So if Europe sees that the new Greek government, in its first year in power, wants to bring order, acts rationally and shows that the country has a strong political will to implement the rescue program, then I am sure that all the commitments that cannot be fulfilled because they lead to a recession can be renegotiated, but only after a certain time.
It would be a mistake to think that we can go back to negotiating with our creditors within the first year of the new agreement, because they expect full implementation of the agreement.
If we want to regain their trust, we must continue the privatisation, reforms and structural changes that have been agreed, while continuing to benefit from EU funding and the great investment opportunities that we must open up for better understanding and cooperation with Europe.
Unfortunately, during the negotiations, the Tsipras government failed to make any serious arguments on many key political issues, as we have learned from discussions with our European counterparts.
I can give you an example of farmers' incomes.
We have explained to our European partners that this is not a fixed monthly income and therefore cannot be fully taxed in advance.
We were told that Tsipras' ministers never mentioned it.
That is, the Greek ministers were unprepared and ill-informed, and therefore failed to negotiate and to conclude a failed agreement.
Evro: If you win the elections, you will soon be sitting at the same table with Mr. Juncker, Mr. Hollande, Mrs. Merkel and other European leaders.
Will what you tell them be different from what your predecessor, Antonis Samaras, told them?
