We pushed for reform.
Of course, we lacked the necessary determination and speed, but we acted in an emergency.
The market had fallen, and there were no potential buyers willing to pay the price set by the Greek government.
I was the Speaker of Parliament at the time, and I managed to get the three parliamentary groups, which then constituted the government majority, to agree on a common position.
Despite their deep ideological differences on key bills, we had a functioning parliament, and this in the presence of populists and extremists, and mass demonstrations outside.
And we managed to bring the country back to a normal situation, which would have continued to improve if the process had not been interrupted by the snap general election that resulted in the December presidential election.
