Does David Cameron know anything else about the Lorax?
One thing every parent learns very quickly is that if your child likes a book, it will take a while for you to know it almost by heart.
I guess, unless you are David Cameron.
When asked by a company that provides holiday packages for children about his favourite children's book, the Prime Minister chose The Lorax, an environmentally-oriented story written by Dr. Seuss in 1971.
It was a difficult choice, Cameron wrote in a comment posted on the SuperCamps website, and continues: "This funny, moving, unusual story with a strong message I love to read to my children, because there is always some image or message that we are missing".
And all would be well except for the last paragraph, where Cameron is supposed to retell the book's content, but actually tells the plot of the 2012 film of the same name, with new characters and details added to diversify the rather short original narrative.
"In the walled city of Allnutville, where there was no greenery and even the air was sold for money, a boy named Ted hopes to win the heart of Audrey, the girl of his dreams, by fulfilling her wish to see a real tree", the text reads, describing the love story of the unknown Dr. Seuss (real name Theodore Seuss Geisel), who died in 1991.
If that doesn't sound suspicious enough, Cameron's text reads almost like a synopsis of the plot of "The Lorax" posted on the Internet Movie Database: "In the high-walled city of All-Nuskyville, where everything was artificial and even air was for sale, a boy named Ted hopes to win the heart of Audrey, the girl of his dreams".
It seems unlikely that Cameron, a self-confessed active parent, is so unfamiliar with the content of a book in which an unnamed boy learns about the environmental destruction of greedy tree-cutter and "all-purpose" knitter Nakhodkins, despite protests from Lorax (whose name is in the book's title) - a funny creature with a mustache who "speaks for the trees".
It's likely that such a simple PR task was given to a performer who had never read a child a book about the Lorax 20 times in a row.
A Downing Street spokeswoman said the text was allegedly obtained from Cameron's office in the constituency.
SuperCamps confirmed that the text was obtained from Cameron's headquarters, but no further comment was forthcoming.
