Experts criticise the review of e-cigarettes by Public Health England
The claims by the government-funded agency that e-cigarettes are 95 percent less harmful than smoking were made by 12 people at the meeting, some of whom are associated with the tobacco industry, the researchers said.
Experts published in the British Medical Journal (BMJ) along with the Lancet have criticised the evidence used by Public Health England (PHE) in its report on e-cigarettes.
PHE released a landmark report last month, calling it a "comprehensive review of the evidence".
But some researchers have questioned the accuracy of the data and pointed to the association of some experts with the tobacco industry.
An editorial in the medical journal Lancet last month criticized the "extremely shaky argument" on which PHE based its main conclusion.
In the BMJ article, two other researchers questioned whether these claims had "strong or shaky grounds".
Martin McKee, a lecturer in European health organization at the London School of Hygiene and Tropical Medicine, and Simon Capewell, a lecturer in clinical epidemiology at the University of Liverpool, reported: "The fundamental principle of health policy is that it should be based on evidence of effectiveness".
They said the public would expect PHE's assertion that "the current best estimate shows e-cigarettes to be about 95% less harmful than tobacco smoking" to be based on a detailed examination of the evidence and modelling.
In fact, this is from a single meeting of 12 people who came together to develop a model of a multi-criteria decision analysis to summarize their views on the harms associated with various nicotine-containing products; the results of the meeting are summarized in a scientific publication.
McKee and Capewell reported that one of the sponsors of the meeting was a company called EuroSwiss Health, whose CEO was reported to have previously received funding from British American Tobacco for independent research.
It also confirmed BAT certifications in the health sector in a sustainability report.
One of the 12 people at the meeting announced funding from the e-cigarette manufacturer, without mentioning the funding he had previously reportedly received from the Philip Morris tobacco company.
No reasonable explanation for the selection of the council members was provided, but there are several prominent e-cigarette advocates among them, some of whom also claimed industry funding in the publication.
It's not clear if the other participants in the meeting have any management experience in the tobacco business.
The meeting was also attended by the head of the tobacco department at PHE.
The scientific paper published by the group "strongly agrees" that there is a lack of "serious evidence of harmful effects of most products on most criteria", McKee and Capewell wrote.
However, none of these connections and limitations were addressed in the PHE report.
McKee and Capwell said that PHE's claim that "there is no evidence at this time that e-cigarettes are a route that leads children or non-smokers to smoke" is premature.
Professor Kevin Fenton, head of health and wellbeing at PHE, said the BMJ had responded to the statements earlier.
He said: "E-cigarettes are far less harmful than tobacco smoking".
One of the two lifelong smokers died from his addiction.
All the evidence suggests that the health risks from e-cigarettes are relatively small, but we need to continue to study the long-term effects.
PHE has a clear duty to inform the public about what this evidence does and does not prove, especially where the public has had doubts about the relative hazards compared to tobacco.
About 80,000 people a year die from smoking-related illnesses, and smoking costs the NHS £2 billion a year.
By clearly stating the obvious - that while e-cigarettes are not safe, they cause only a fraction of the harm that smoking does - we are fulfilling our mission to the nation.
