Sonogenetics allows you to control brain cells with sound waves
In this video, you can see how the nematodes change direction when they are exposed to sound.
Scientists have produced worms with a genetically modified nervous system that can be controlled using pulses of sound waves.
Tiny nematodes change direction when they are hit by sound pulses that are too loud for the human ear to hear.
The impulses exert their effects by activating neurons genetically engineered to use membrane channels that respond to ultrasound waves.
Also in this issue: Researchers control brain activity with light
The scientists said the worms are demonstrating a new technique called sonogenetics, which involves using ultrasound to stimulate specific cells in the brain, heart and muscles, with the ultrasound source located outside the body.
Shrikant Chalsani, a research fellow at the Salk Institute in La Jolla, California, told the Guardian that the technique could one day replace deep brain stimulation, an invasive procedure that sends electrical impulses to the brain and is used to treat Parkinson's disease.
The nematode worms normally don't respond to ultrasound, but Chalasani found that they started to respond when they were placed in a liquid containing microscopic bubbles.
He found that the bubbles amplified the ultrasonic waves, which then penetrated the worms' bodies.
The enhanced ultrasound waves act on structures called "TRP-4 ion channels", found in the membranes of some worm cells.
The ultrasonic waves cause these ion channels to open and excite the cells that are connected to them, reports a report in Nature Communications.
To create nematodes that could be manipulated by ultrasound, Chalasani genetically modified worms so that their motor neurons used TRP-4 ion channels.
When ultrasound was used to target the modified organisms, the sound waves were amplified by microscopic bubbles and introduced into the worm organism, activating the modified motor neurons.
This technique is similar to that used in optogenetics, a new field that allows scientists to turn neurons on and off with light pulses.
Chalasani argues that sonogenetics may have some advantages over this technique.
Unlike light, which is delivered to the right part of the brain by optical fiber, low-frequency ultrasound waves travel freely through body tissues, so they don't need to go inside the skull to be delivered.
"We believe that the use of gene therapy and therapeutic viruses to treat certain neurological diseases in clinical settings could temporarily make human neurons sensitive to ultrasound", said Chalasani.
He added that the technique could also be applied to muscle and insulin-producing cells.
