The eight golden rules of living in student housing
It's been 11 years since I moved into a dorm room as a normal 19-year-old, still believing in the Berets and moral relativism, but only now do I remember the elongated smiles of those I've annoyed - and the numerous, long complaints about others.
Most of what I've learned can be broken down into eight simple rules.
Moving into a dorm can range from mildly nerve-wracking to downright frightening.
He encourages you to talk, to tell people where you're from, whether you took a sabbatical and where you spent it, whether you support Corbin and why you "honestly don't love or hate Marmite, because seriously, guys, it's just yeast extract, I'll be fine".
Take a breath. You know what?
And help others to rest too - ask questions and show interest.
It keeps the conversation going and helps you find people you like, not people you wouldn't talk to if your wrists were on fire and they were handing out fire extinguishers.
Give the people some space.
People's bedrooms often become drinking establishments, midnight movie theaters and social clubs, but they are also places where people dress and mend their underwear.
And on a related note, don't even think about going to college while you're in a relationship.
Introverts are treated unfairly in universities.
Your room should be a place of refuge, but many dormitories create a culture of moving from one room to another, which fosters friendships, relationships, and leads to long-term relationships.
It can be hell for someone trying to regain their strength.
There's nothing in the culture that allows you to say, "I like you, and I want to be friends with you, but I need you to go away so I can recoup the energy I've spent talking to you".
Try to sense when a classmate is tired of communication - and not knock on him, but send a text.
Speaking of knocking, do that.
There was a guy in my dorm who had a policy that if the door was unlocked, he was invited in.
He saw something.
Make friends with a bakery.
Because you're starting college at the height of the Bake-Off, knocking on people's doors to introduce yourself and hand them a plate of chocolate biscuits is not so strange anymore, not so reminiscent of the 1950s with their "Welcome, we're neighbors, I've baked you something, now smile, and I'll ask you personal questions".
Offering homemade treats is a great way to make friends.
Your neighbors will feel obliged to chat with you, and eventually, your face will likely be associated with a pleasant surprise.
Of course, that depends on how good a baker you are.
Poorly glued flour, sugar and fat will make people pretend to be asleep when you knock on their door.
Stealing food is a common crime in student dormitories.
Sure, it's stealing to steal someone else's chicken, but is it stealing to take a little milk for tea?
You can take it from the milk man.
He'll probably offer you the benefit of the doubt, even if you're burning with rage.
If someone steals your stuff, it's annoying, and I sympathize with you, but try to treat this adult like my neighbor who poured dishwashing fluid into her milk to get back at those who took it without asking.
She's in prison now.
You must not make any noise that will disturb people's sleep or study.
Not just to be a decent person, but because you're the same people that are in the glass house saying.
The girl in my hallway asked my neighbor to turn down the drum and bass, because it was 3:00 in the morning and she had an exam in the morning.
The neighbor raised the volume in response.
When he finally stopped at 5 a.m., she graciously let him sleep for two hours, then handed him her music and locked the door behind her, heading for a three-hour exam.
Wouldn't it be romantic if your future husband and wife were living in the same dorm room as you?
On the contrary, wouldn't it be extremely, elbow-biting, awkward if you had mistaken your neighbor for your future spouse, fallen for him, broken off the relationship and had to see him every day, and perhaps watch him pull all your mutual friends to his side?
Of course, you can't touch the heart - but if the hot neighbor is definitely not your future husband, try to cool your own fire a little.
In that exciting moment when you realize someone left the keys inside their locked room, the line between a prank and a bully is thinner than it looks.
A good prank is fun, but it turns into its opposite in a matter of seconds.
Teach a valuable and interesting safety lesson by hiding something - but never dirty someone's room with toothpaste and shampoo.
Lock someone's door and put the keys in a glass of water that you'll put in the freezer later - but don't stick someone else's stuff with Blu-Tack to the ceiling more than twice.
