In turn, experts note that the main problem is the complete lack of infrastructure for the storage, maintenance and maintenance of yachts.
Owners prefer to store their vessels abroad - about €200 million annually goes to the European state treasury for the maintenance, repair and maintenance of yachts.
The Ministry of Economic Development of Russia has prepared a draft decision of the Council of the Eurasian Economic Commission "On Amending the List of Goods Temporarily Imported with Full Conditional Exemption from Customs Duties and Taxes", providing for full conditional exemption from customs duties and taxes in respect of imported yachts and other floating means for recreation and sport.
According to the Ministry, this will certainly contribute to the creation of favorable conditions for the development of yachting in the coastal zones of the country, - said Lashkina.
This issue was brought to the attention of the subcommittee on customs-tariff, non-tariff regulation, protective measures in foreign trade of the Government Commission on Economic Development and Integration, whose meeting was held in September, and was also approved by the departments as a result of the discussion.
As the representative of the Ministry of Economic Development noted, the proposed measure of full conditional release upon importation is essentially a benefit.
Therefore, after the approval of the minutes of the meeting of the subcommission in the government of the Russian Federation, the Ministry of Economic Development will make a proposal to the Eurasian Economic Commission for discussion with the member states of the EAEU, Lashkina explained.
The list of imported goods that are fully exempt from payment of customs duties, taxes, includes goods necessary for the promotion of foreign economic activities and international cooperation, for use in the field of science, culture, cinematography, sports and tourism, for the provision of international assistance, etc. Among them - service equipment (personal computers, typewriters), control and measurement instruments, drilling equipment, stage costumes and decorations, mobile laboratories and workshops, water skies, gonocars, motorcycles, sports flying machines, books, newspapers, magazines, musical instruments and items for religious rites.
The press service of the Ministry of Transport of the Russian Federation told "Izvestia" that they have prepared mandatory regulations for the seaports of Kerch, Sevastopol, Yalta, Feodosia and Epatoria, which provide for a simplified procedure for the registration of entry and exit of small-sized, sports sailing and pleasure boats in the sea port.
The Ministry of Transport has instructed the captains of the sea ports of Crimea to ensure the application of a simplified order of entry of small-sized, sports sailing and pleasure vessels into the sea port and the exit of the listed vessels from the sea port.
The Ministry of Transport has also prepared draft orders of the Russian government on the approval of the borders of the waters of the sea ports of the Crimea.
The orders have already been adopted for Yalta and Feodosia, the rest are in the process of being agreed, - said in the press service of the department.
According to the Ministry of Transport, the state supervision, classification and certification, state registration in respect of small-sized vessels used for non-commercial purposes should be carried out by the Republic of Crimea and Sevastopol.
The problem is that Russia is extremely difficult with yachting precisely because of the poorly developed infrastructure.
