Kiev has dismantled the nuclear union.
Kiev has formally formalised Ukraine's refusal to cooperate with Russia on the completion of the Khmelnytskyi nuclear power plant.
The Verkhovna Rada on Wednesday voted to terminate the agreement with Moscow.
Agreements on the completion of the third and fourth blocks were signed in 2010-2012, but it was not possible to start implementing the project.
On Wednesday, the Verkhovna Rada of Ukraine adopted a law that terminates the agreement with Russia on the construction of the third and fourth units at the Khmelnytskyi nuclear power plant, which was concluded in 2010-2012.
The bill introduced by the government was passed only after the second vote, the first time it was supported by 210 deputies with the necessary minimum of 226, but then when the bill was voted for by 234 members of parliament.
The Khmelnitsky NPP, built during the USSR, was originally planned to have four 1 GW power units with VVER reactors, but only two were built.
Negotiations with Moscow on the completion of the project led to the conclusion of an intergovernmental agreement in 2010, and in 2011-2012 the Rada adopted the relevant laws.
Since there were no funds in the budget of Ukraine, it was assumed that the construction of the blocks would have to be on the credit of the Russian side, but the funds were never allocated.
After the coup in Kiev in February 2014 and the subsequent cooling of relations between the two countries, Kiev began to curtail relations with Moscow in the atomic industry, announcing its refusal to cooperate on the Khmelnytsky NPP and the project to build a nuclear fuel plant in Ukraine.
The only area where relations remained, was the purchase of fuel in the Russian Federation for the operating Ukrainian NPPs (which provided about half of the electricity production in the country), since so far the Ukrainian NAEC "Energoatom" could not replace the Russian supplies.
Plans to complete the construction of the Khmelnytsky NPP with another contractor in Ukraine have not yet been definitively abandoned: back in 2014, Kiev announced talks with the Czech Skoda JS.
