The company said it still expects revenue growth over the past year due to reduced costs, higher gross income and growth in online sales.
Chairman and CEO Fred Smith stated that the company "operated steadily in light of weak, compared to forecast, economic conditions, especially in manufacturing and global trade".
The holiday hiring plans were announced the day after rival UPS announced that they planned to hire an additional 95,000 employees, about the same number as they hired last year.
For the quarter ended August 31, FedEx earned $692 million, up 6 percent from a year earlier.
Earnings per share were $2.42, close to the average of $2.44 per share predicted by Zacks Investment Research's poll of 12 analysts.
Revenue increased 5% to $12.3 billion.
The six analysts Zacks interviewed were guessing $12.23 billion.
FedEx has suffered in recent years from a downturn in the international express sector, which has resulted in no growth in gross revenue in its express division.
However, the boom in online shopping has dramatically improved FedEx Ground's results.
In the last quarter, ground handling revenues grew by 29%, but operating revenues remained broadly unchanged due to higher costs for large shipments and self-insurance.
The express division had higher revenue due to higher base rates, while the freight division had lower revenue due to higher labor costs.
In a preliminary trading session about an hour before the stock market opened, FedEx shares fell $3.85, or 2.5 percent, to $150.15.
They closed Tuesday, down 11 percent year-to-date and 17 percent below the June 11 record.
In the most anticipated meeting in years, the Fed heads will spend two days this week at a 27-foot table of Honduran redwood, deciding whether it's time to raise the key interest rate for the first time in nearly a decade.
At one end of the richly decorated two-story-high conference room, a mural of the United States will hang above them.
This map is a reminder that Federal Reserve Chair Janet L. Yellen and her colleagues must put the economic interests of the country above all others.
The central bank has a dual mandate from Congress: to maximize employment in the United States and to keep prices stable.
But since the Great Recession, the heads of the Federal Reserve have recognized that there is a third, unwritten mandate: financial stability.
And this third mandate may prove to be the unknown factor in the almost predictable decision to be announced on Thursday as to whether the US economy is ready to shake off the unprecedented stimulus provided by the near-zero short-term interest rate since late 2008.
Even though most of the data is showing solid economic growth, the recent turmoil in global financial markets may be deterring already cautious Federal Reserve officials from adding to the volatility by raising the federal funds rate by as little as a quarter of a percentage point.
"It is clear that the labour market and inflation will be the first and most important subject of consideration", said Lindsey M. Peigza, chief economist at brokerage firm Stifel Nicolaus & Co.
"However, I think if they were looking for a reason not to raise rates, the increased uncertainty around the global market is enough to give them an excuse to wait further", she noted.
There is no consensus on what to do in the Federal Reserve, which in itself causes financial market fluctuations.
About half the economists recently polled by Bloomberg predicted that interest rates would rise this week.
Financial markets, however, expect the Federal Reserve to hold off on this, with the key indicator showing only a roughly 30% chance of a quick recovery.
It could cause a stock market crash if the Federal Reserve raises the rate, provided that those who make the decisions don't soften the blow by promising that the next rate increase will be soon.
On Tuesday, the Dow Jones Industrial Average rose 228.89 points, or 1.4%, to 16,599.85.
The surge was triggered by expectations that the Federal Reserve's policy makers would quit this week, said John Lonsky, chief economist at Moody's Capital Markets Research Group.
"It would be a surprise if the Federal system were to raise rates at this point in time", he remarked.
If the Fed does this, "they will have to go a long way in their strategy of keeping the financial markets in check so that they don't panic".
Other experts argued that raising the rate would calm financial markets, as it would remove uncertainty about how the Federal Reserve System would operate.
Just a month ago, the Federal Reserve seemed to be leaning towards raising rates by 0.25% this month, making the first small step in a slow tightening of financial conditions that could confirm the strength of the US recovery.
Yellen said in the spring and early summer that she expected a rate hike this year, despite complaints from the Liberals that more economic progress was needed.
Although job creation slowed in August, labour market growth was steady this year.
Unemployment fell to 5.1% last month, the lowest in more than seven years, and near what the Federal system considers full employment.
Wage growth is showing signs of accelerating.
And while inflation remains below the central bank's target of 2 percent per year, the Fed's leadership has said that the key cause is the temporary effect of the sharp drop in oil prices.
The economy "can handle higher rates, and needs them, given the shrinking labor market", noted Ian Shephardson, chief economist at Pantheon Macroeconomics.
However, financial markets around the world began to rattle late last month after China devalued its currency.
The Dow Jones Industrial Average fell as much as 16% from a record high in May as investors feared that a slowdown in the Chinese economy could dampen global growth.
The market has partially recovered this month, and the Dow Jones is now about 10% below its May high.
For the Fed, market turmoil complicates the complex calculations of the timeline for the interest rate hike.
"In the absence of information about what happened in the financial markets and news about the weakness of the Chinese economy in the last few weeks, they would have been screwing up at this meeting", said Stephen D. Oliner, a senior researcher at the UCLA Ziman Center for Real Estate and a former Federal Reserve official.
Now, he predicts they'll wait at least a month to get more control of the fallout.
"There is a lot of uncertainty about what the impact might be on the US economy, and they have very little reliable data after the recent events in China", said Oliner.
The health of the world economy is not a primary concern of the Federal System, and technically it should not be a factor in making those decisions.
But essentially the Federal Reserve has become the world's financial power.
The influence of the central bank in recent years has been enormous.
A single hint from then-Chairman Ben S. Bernanke in 2013 that the Federal Reserve could "muffle" its monetary expansion caused a worldwide market upheaval.
In a world where markets and economic systems are increasingly intertwined, one would expect that Fed officials would not only monitor developments everywhere, but also consult with representatives of other central banks and experts to better understand the global economy.
Their decision-making process is "more of an art than a science", said Zachary Karabell, CEO of Envestnet Inc., a company that deals with global wealth management strategies.
Jeffrey Lacker, president of the Federal Reserve Bank of Richmond, Virginia, noted this month that "there have been cases in the history of the Federal Reserve of overreacting to financial market movements that do not seem to be related to economic principles".
Lacker, a voting member of the influential Federal Open Market Committee, insisted on a rate increase, citing the 1998-99 decisions as an example.
The Asian financial crisis led the Fed to lower its base rate by 0.75% in three sessions, "despite limited identifiable effects on U.S. growth", Lacker said.
A year later, the Federal System heads reversed those cuts.
The Federal Reserve should only prioritize stability during major crises, such as the 2008 market crash", said Adam S. Posen, a former member of the Bank of England's interest rate committee.
The latest panic was nowhere near that level, he said.
"You don't want to be in a situation where you're afraid of rising rates because markets are in a state of shock", said Posen, president of the Peterson Institute for Global Economics.
The Federal Reserve Act still has a dual mandate and no mention of financial stability, and until that changes, I don't think they should be ahead of the curve.
