Four people, including a 4-year-old boy, were killed in southern Nepal when police opened fire with rubber bullets at a crowd protesting the country's proposed new constitution, an official said on Wednesday.
The violence occurred late Tuesday in Rupandey district, about 175 miles west of the country's capital, Kathmandu.
Bishnu Prasad Dhakal, the district police chief, said that more than 1,000 protesters gathered outside one of the police stations, some throwing stones and incendiary bombs.
