For diabetics with a low level of obesity, obesity surgery may be helpful
The beneficial effect of weight-loss surgery in people with mild obesity who have type 2 diabetes can last for at least five years, according to a new study.
However, it is too early to say that diabetics with moderate obesity live longer after obesity surgery than those who receive nonsurgical treatment.
"The mortality statistics are not coming out right away", said Dr. Robin Blackstone, an expert in obesity surgery who wrote about the new study in the editorial column of JAMA Surgery.
Bariatric surgery, or obesity surgery, uses various techniques to reduce the size of the stomach.
They reduce hunger and limit the body's ability to digest food.
Bariatric surgery has been shown to be effective in treating type 2 diabetes for several years, but the main studies have been in people with morbid obesity, with a body mass index (BMI) of 35 or higher.
BMI, a measure of weight relative to height, is considered normal when it is between 18.5 and 24.9.
A BMI of 25 or higher indicates that a person is overweight, and people with a BMI of 30 or higher are considered obese.
You can calculate your BMI here: 1.usa.gov/1D0ZqDv.
For the new study, researchers at Taiwan's Min-Sheng General Hospital used data collected since 2007 to compare two types of bariatric surgery - gastric bypass and sleeve gastrectomy - with medical treatment of type 2 diabetes in people with mild obesity.
The average BMI of those who underwent surgery fell from 31 to 24.5 by the end of the fifth year of the study.
Meanwhile, those who have been treated for diabetes without surgery have a BMI of about 29.
Of those who had the surgery, 36 percent were completely cured of diabetes and 28 percent were partially cured.
In comparison, the control group had only 1 percent of complete diabetes and only about 2 percent of partial diabetes.
Also, blood pressure, triglycerides, and "bad" LDL cholesterol "were generally better in the surgical group", the authors state.
The researchers also monitored the levels of hemoglobin A1c in the blood, which reflects the blood sugar levels in the dynamics.
A1c is best kept below 7 percent, the researchers write.
After surgery, the average hemoglobin A1c dropped from about 9% to about 6%.
In the treatment group, however, it remained stable at about 8%.
But better glycemic control, reflected in good hemoglobin A1c levels, did not reduce the five-year mortality rate, according to study leader Dr. Chi-Cheng Soo and colleagues.
The research team also compared the average outcomes of two types of surgical treatment.
By the fifth year, the shunt group lost more weight (18.7 kg vs. 14.2 kg) than the sleeve gastrectomy group, had a greater reduction in BMI (7.4 vs. 5.1) and A1c (3.1% vs. 2.1%) than the shunt group, and were closer to complete diabetes remission (46.9% vs. 16.7%).
While the new study does not demonstrate surgical benefits in terms of life expectancy after five years, there is evidence from a study of overweight people in Sweden that surgical treatment does lead to an increase in life expectancy, reports Blackstone of the University of Arizona College of Medicine in Phoenix.
A Swedish study found that the probability of dying over 15 years was about 29% lower for obese people who chose bariatric intervention compared to the group who chose more traditional methods.
Although the new study did not show an increase in life expectancy, Blackstone noted that it was encouraging for people with a BMI below 35 to be interested in such a procedure.
"This report is very important because it says that this surgery is safe in a group with a low BMI, where there is no increased risk of mortality or kidney disease", she said.
Blackstone added that people and their doctors should start taking weight seriously as soon as a patient's BMI falls between the range of 27 and 30.
"I think we've waited too long to get people to take it seriously", she said.
It seems to me that once they accumulate the genetic changes that trigger obesity and diabetes in their bodies, it's very difficult to reverse it.
