Four-fold increase in children swallowing hand sanitizer in the last four years.
Toxicology centers in the United States have reported an almost 400 percent increase since 2010 in the number of children under 12 years of age who ingested alcohol-based hand sanitizer, according to the Georgia State Toxicology Center.
According to Dr. Gaylord Lopez, director of the Georgia State Toxicology Center, the number of hand sanitizer ingestions reported to the centers by children under 12 years of age increased from 3,266 in 2010 to 16,117 in 2014.
"Children are exposed to these substances more often, and unfortunately, a certain percentage of them are sent to the emergency room", Lopez told CNN.
He said that some children drink the disinfectant liquid on purpose, and some do it to impress their friends or to argue for social media.
YouTube videos show teenagers drinking disinfectant as a cheap drink.
Teens reportedly mixed disinfectant with alcohol-containing mouthwash to make a stronger drink.
Younger children may be attracted to the pleasant smell of the disinfectant.
"The child doesn't think it can harm him", Lopez said.
Many of the most attractive hand sanitizers are the ones that are flavored.
There are hand sanitizers with the smell of strawberries, grapes, oranges, which are very appealing to children.
Hand sanitizer fluid contains anywhere from 45 to 95 percent alcohol.
In young children, especially, just a few sprays can cause alcohol poisoning.
"This is a high-concentration alcohol", said Dr. Stephen Thornton, chief medical officer of the toxicology center at the University of Kansas Hospital, to Fox 4 in Kansas City.
You wouldn't leave a shot of whiskey out, but people keep these hand sanitizers in mind, and if kids get their hands on them, it's a quick way to consume a lot of alcohol.
Naija Russell, a six-year-old girl who recently swallowed a hand sanitizer with a strawberry flavor in the amount of about four sprays, was sent to the emergency room for treatment.
Her blood alcohol level was 179, twice that of an adult who is considered legally intoxicated, according to Dr. Chris Ritchie, the emergency room physician who treated her at Gwinnett Medical Center near Atlanta.
Naija was speechless and unable to walk when she was taken to the emergency room.
Doctors watched her all night in a separate children's clinic to make sure there was no sign of brain injury, as the alcohol caused the girl to fall and hit her head, Ritchie said.
"It was very scary", Orthoria Scott, Naija's mother, told CNN.
It could have been fatal for my child.
Lopes advised parents and teachers to use non-spicy substances or disinfectant wipes, in addition to keeping hand sanitizers out of the reach of children.
Aside from alcohol poisoning, some disinfectant fluids have been linked to deaths.
In 2013, two women in Ontario died after ingesting a disinfectant that contained a toxic, undiagnosed ingredient.
Health officials suspect the product contained methanol, a lethal agent, not the ethanol alcohol that was listed as the active ingredient.
In January, three fourth-grade students in upstate New York conspired to poison their "opposite" teacher by "spreading antibacterial agents in the classroom", according to a police report.
The teacher is allergic to hand sanitizers, and she has banned them from her classroom.
Police believe the failed plan was "empty talk", and are addressing disciplinary issues to the school district.
