Its participants are obliged to track and delete comments that are incorrect in relation to migrants and refugees.
According to Haiko Maas, it is expected that the authors of intolerant posts will receive notifications indicating the reason for the deletion of their posts.
Organisations whose specialists collect complaints from social network users about offensive posts should also contribute to the prompt blocking of illegal content.
Facebook management is committed to providing the financial support they need.
The decision to remove posts containing negative comments about migrants and refugees was made by the social network's management and the German Ministry of Justice after xenophobic sentiments rose sharply in the German segment of Facebook.
One of the most obvious reasons for this is the unprecedented migration crisis that has hit the EU countries recently.
In Germany, for example, refugee resettlement centers are already overcrowded.
The day before, the authorities decided to temporarily settle the migrants in the territory of the former Buchenwald concentration camp.
Forced migrants from the Middle East and Africa are housed in the same barracks that Nazi prisoners and prisoners of war were housed in.
Moscow cemeteries will have relaxation areas.
In the near future, several of the capital's cemeteries will be equipped with special zones for relaxation and psychological rest.
The first will be the Butov, Domodedovo, and the Shcherbin cemetery.
The first psychological rest area has already been established at the Troyekurovsky Cemetery in Moscow.
In the future, similar sites will appear in other areas of the city.
This was reported by Artem Ekimov, the head of the State budgetary institution "Ritual".
The relaxation areas will be small landscaped areas, reminiscent of parks.
Experts believe that such "corners" are a place where visitors can relax, be alone, and regain their psychological strength.
In the near future, relaxation zones will be built in Domodedovo, Butov and Shcherbin cemeteries, and then in other areas of the capital.
According to the head of the Ritual State Cemetery, if the cemetery needs to be expanded, the builders will try to preserve the existing forest areas as much as possible.
The green spaces will serve as a living fence that will separate the recreation areas and the areas set aside directly for the burial sites.
The Ritual State Bureau of Experts also announced their intention to propose the abolition of the burial fences.
New cemeteries can really become barrier-free.
In addition, the Ritual State Cemetery Office said it was ready to install electronic terminals, with the help of which visitors to cemeteries can learn the GPS coordinates and number signs of burials.
In June this year, Ritual also proposed to adjust the cost of funeral services depending on the time of year.
