The processes of globalization were supposed to help reduce inequality in the world.
In fact, the reality is that the income gap in developing economies is actually growing.
Eric Maskin.
To remedy this, education levels of low-skilled workers need to be improved, says Eric Maskin, chief scientist of the International Laboratory for Decision Analysis and Choice at the National Institute of Economic Research, and winner of the 2007 Nobel Prize in Economics.
The world has experienced unprecedented growth in global markets over the past 20 years.
Trade borders between countries became more and more open.
Proponents of globalization predicted great benefits for emerging economies.
"And those predictions have largely come true", Maskin points out.
China and India, for example, have seen significant GDP per capita growth.
But it's not all that glowing.
Globalization was expected to reduce the gap between the "haves" and the "have-nots" in poor countries, which is manifested in the great inequality of income, or more precisely, of wages.
But in fact, inequality has only increased, notes Eric Maskin in his article "Why Global Markets Have Failed to Reduce Inequality in Emerging Economies", published in The World Bank Economic Review, translated and quoted by the IEA.
Together with Harvard University economist Michael Kremer, Professor Eric Maskin has developed an alternative theory that demonstrates why income inequality in poor countries is increasing as globalization increases, the HSE reminds.
The new global market is undergoing a specific process.
To illustrate this, Muskine identifies four levels of qualification for professionals: A and B for rich countries, C and D for poor countries.
After globalization, D specialists from poor countries are not qualified to cooperate with A and B specialists from rich countries.
And while the C workers in poor countries are getting their pay raised by working with B workers in rich countries, the D workers are not getting their pay raised or are getting their pay cut.
The net effect is that the internationalization of production will increase the wage gap between the two categories of professionals in poor countries and thus increase inequality.
Cremer and E. Maskin have proposed a surprisingly beautiful model, an alternative to the Ricardian theory of comparative advantage.
It helps explain why globalization has led to income inequality", says Fuad Aleshkerov, professor emeritus, head of the International Laboratory for Analysis and Decision Making, head of the mathematics department at the National Institute of Higher Education.
And like any powerful theory, I'm sure it will lead to a flurry of empirical work in this area.
The solution, according to Eric Maskin, is to increase the education of low-skilled workers.
However, the workers themselves, as the scientist notes, do not have the means to do so, and it is not profitable for companies to pay for their training.
Governments, international agencies, NGOs and private foundations can play a significant role in this situation, according to Maskin.
The scientist notes that the developed theory in no way calls for stopping the process of globalization, which has brought and is bringing its fruits in the form of GDP growth of countries.
Derbent: a living link to the times.
Derbent, one of the oldest cities in Russia, is celebrating its 2000th anniversary in September.
The program of the festive events - festival of national cultures of the peoples of Dagestan and a fair in the style of the past times, an exhibition of derbent carpets and the Open Temples Day, a historical-musical show "2000 years in two hours" and an excursion to the reconstructed Peter I Museum.
The medieval stones of the Naryn Kala fortress, the ancient Arabic inscriptions on the walls, the narrow streets and the palace gardens - all this is as if it came from the pages of "The Thousand and One Nights".
Derbent is the only city in Russia that has been preserved in its place since ancient times.
Although it was claimed by the Roman Empire, Byzantium, the Khazar Khanate and the Golden Horde.
The eastern plane trees that grow in the courtyard of the Durban Juma mosque are several centuries old.
These mighty plants are protected by the All-Russia program "Trees - Monuments of Living Nature".
The shade of the radiant towers provides a refuge for pilgrims and tourists during the summer heat.
The visitor is served with fragrant tea and Dagestani delicacies - honeyed figs, dates, mushrooms, miracle cakes, ayran and sweets.
In Derbent, large samovars have been used for centuries to serve tea to numerous guests at once.
The inscription above the entrance to the Jumma mosque says that the building was built in the year 115 Hijra.
That's 733 on the Gregorian calendar.
It's the oldest mosque in Russia.
The interior is striking in its grandeur and solemnity: the arches of the domes and vaults are supported by square columns and are illuminated by the rays of the sun from tiny windows.
The keeping and breeding of pigeons is a traditional hobby of the inhabitants of Derbent.
Bird owners keep pigeon-houses in their yards, under trees, in attics.
The spectacle is a flock of white doves, which look like the flashes of a festive fireworks display.
In order to protect the ancient Persians from the enemy, they blocked the Caspian Gate with a double stone wall.
The structure, which extends 500 meters into the sea, blocks the harbor of Derbent.
In 2003, the Derbent fortress walls were included in the UNESCO World Heritage List as the best preserved monument of ancient Persian fortification architecture.
Carpets were woven in Derbent as early as the fifth century, and the technology of this unique craft has remained virtually unchanged to this day.
On one of the streets adjacent to the city market, carpets for every taste are sold - strips of wool, cotton, or wool in all colors and shades, with hair and without, with intricate ornaments and a whimsical border.
The city began with the construction of the maghals - quarters with one-story stone buildings.
Over the years, the Mughals have changed little.
Satellite dishes, wall-mounted air conditioners, and street lamps are the only things that remind you that you are not in a medieval city but in a modern one.
In the old part of the city, there are still parts of a water supply system built by the Persians about a thousand years ago.
The ancient springs have survived to this day, and the local people still draw water from them.
Many Derbent residents prefer tap water to water from historic fountains.
Derbent was one of the centers of the pottery trade.
The vessels, dishes, cups, and cups used for drinking were prized throughout the Caucasus.
The potter's hands still produce fine ceramic objects for practical and souvenir purposes.
On holidays and festivals, crowds of spectators gather under the wire rope, on which the students of the Republican School of Circus Art perform.
The history of this amazing and risky craft goes back centuries.
A new trend is that more and more girls are being seen among the tightrope walkers.
The former Virgin Bath is now the home of the Museum of the Culture and Life of Ancient Derbent.
Unmarried girls and brides used to bathe here accompanied by their friends, but now anyone can see the domed hall, hot and cold pools, and bathing facilities that have passed into the past.
Most houses in Derbent have hot water, but the baths and steam rooms are as popular today as they were in the old days.
The benefits of steam heating are written in old books.
After the bath, blood flow improves, muscle fatigue disappears, and the body becomes more flexible and agile.
The festival "Solidarity", which takes place on the territory of the fortress of Naryn-Kala, is attended by ethnic couples from many districts of Dagestan.
Participants in national costumes dance, play folk melodies, sing songs of the peoples of the Caucasus and treat visitors with delicious homemade cheese.
The Kyrklyar is the burial place of forty martyrs who laid down their heads for Islam.
It is one of the most revered complexes for Muslims of the North Caucasus.
The sarcophagi, which have become yellow over time, are carved from solid stone blocks and oriented, as is customary among the Arabs, on the west-east axis.
Brothers Gavril and Albert Yakubov cut and shave customers in a small salon near the Upper Bazaar.
The barbershop has been in this location for years.
The techniques of the curling craft are passed down from generation to generation.
The Jacobov brothers can do not only traditional, but also the most modern hairstyle.
On one of the streets of the Old City, a house was preserved in which lived the writer-decembrist Alexander Bestuzhev-Marlinski, who was exiled to the Caucasus.
Having learned the Turkic language and collected ethnographic material, he described the Derbent of the first third of the XIX century with its ancient monuments, the life and everyday life of the townspeople.
The Teahouse is a traditional Oriental club, where only tea and homemade pastries are served.
Men come here to quench their thirst, talk to their friends, and solve some work problems.
As in the past, women are not allowed to enter the teahouse.
The Derbent dance ensemble "Kaspi" was created three years ago, but has already managed to take part in events of the republican and Russian level.
The soloists of the ensemble rehearse every day, perfectly mastering the folk Avar, Dargin, Tat, Armenian dances.
As the noise dies down and the street lights are lit, the locals sit on benches near the houses with their terraces.
Usually, the Derbent discusses the issues of the day.
But as the anniversary approaches, they are increasingly recalling the episodes of their city's unique history, which influenced the fate of the entire Black Sea-Caspian region.
