The U.S. Embassy regrets the closure of the American Center in Moscow.
The American Embassy in Russia expressed regret over the closure of the American Center for Foreign Literature at the Library.
The center has been operating in Moscow for more than 22 years.
The U.S. Embassy in Moscow deeply regrets the Russian government's unilateral decision to close the American Center of the U.S. Embassy at the All-Russian State Library named after M.I. Rudomino in Moscow.
"The unilateral steps taken by the Russian Federation in recent times call into question the commitment of the Russian government to the ties between the Russian and American peoples, which were not interrupted even during the Cold War and other difficult moments in the long history of relations between our countries", said the statement of US Ambassador John Tefft, received by Interfax.
The American Center has created deep and lasting connections between the people and cultures of Russia and the United States.
It was the center of American culture, history and literature in the Russian capital, and also served as a meeting place for numerous prominent American figures, among whom were astronauts, artists, athletes, scientists, politicians and writers.
"Last year alone, the American Center hosted more than 400 cultural and educational events and welcomed more than 50,000 Russian visitors", the diplomat stressed.
Tefft recalled that about a year ago, it was decided to close another joint Russian-American project - the FLEX (Future Leaders Exchange Program) educational exchange program.
The Green Tribunal was quick to execute.
A typical situation: four officials stand in front of the judge Swatantra Kumar's desk, listening to his grievances about the work done.
The court is completely dissatisfied with the quality of your work.
We did not give you a 110-page order to make fun of", says Kumar.
If there's another brick, we'll have to tear down the existing structures.
Kumar heads the National Green Tribunal (NGT), a judicial body established in 2010 to stop the rapid environmental pollution that has accompanied the rapid economic growth of recent decades.
During that time, the Tribunal has handled over 10,000 claims related to air pollution, garbage collection, geological development, toxic waste and dam construction.
In two out of three cases, the court decides to stop the construction that is causing the pollution.
The stakes are incredibly high: in less than 60 years since the declaration of independence, with the intensified industrial development, India has transformed from a country of virgin jungles into one of the most overcrowded and polluted countries in the world.
The problem is particularly acute in large cities, where infrastructure development is lagging behind rapid urbanization: cities are covered with dense smog, rivers are filled with pesticides and waste from enterprises and households, and the few remaining residential areas are being cut down for new residential quarters.
Despite the formal support of the green movement by the state, the NHT is regularly criticized by the Narendra Modi government, as it is often the main reason for the cancellation of major investment projects.
In May of this year, the Minister of the Environment called the court's decisions "extreme" and "impracticable".
Sometimes it is really impossible to enforce a court's decision within the time limit set by the court, as environmental lawyer Raj Panjwani confirms.
But there's a silver lining to missed deadlines: At the very least, they force the responsible ones to move.
"His main goal is to shake up the system", adds the lawyer.
The Green Tribunal has repeatedly canceled major construction projects, including the airport, the power plant, and hundreds of smaller projects.
But people are also being considered, as was the case when a pharmaceutical company in Telangana State polluted a local river with fluoride.
We can shut down your factory, but we're also responsible for the economic consequences.
"People will lose their jobs", Kumar commented on his decision.
However, such explanations are not always understood by the common people, whose lives can be changed by a single stroke of the judge's pen.
In April, the tribunal decided to ban all vehicles older than 10 years from entering the capital, which caused public outrage.
Despite a sharp drop in popularity and a flurry of criticism, Swantar Kumar refused to overturn this decision.
Instead, he ordered the Delhi government to provide statistics on the traffic coming in and going out, and also proposed to buy 10,000 additional buses, after first asking the factories whether they could fulfill such an order.
As pollution sources such as landfills, fuel quality, and even traffic accidents came into the court's attention, public anger began to subside.
But the most painful topic for the principle judge was the Ganga river cleanup programme, which was announced with pomp by Prime Minister Narendra Modi last year.
When it comes to the Ganga, a sacred river for Hindus, the judge often loses control of his emotions and goes on a rampage.
Do you know what the word "sacred" means?
Someone poured water from the Ganges on the statue of God, and it turned out to be fecal matter, - the judge is hot.
You keep polluting the river because you think the Gang is the Gang, it will take away all our sins.
This is the river we worship, and look what you do with it every day.
The Ganga cleanup is the most ambitious and costly environmental project announced by the new government.
Now, the amount of fecal bacteria in this river is more than 120 times the normal amount.
Each year, 1.5 to 3 of the 700 million bathing Hindus die from infectious diseases.
In February, Narendra Modi even donated to the Ganges Salvation Fund the proceeds from the sale of his suit, in which he met Barack Obama, and 455 items from his personal collection.
Environmentalists immediately accused the prime minister of being a populist: the suit was bought for $700,000, while the river needed at least eight billion to be cleaned.
The Green Tribunal's supporters agree that India has a long way to go before it can call itself a developed country, but they do not believe that progress should come at the cost of the environment.
"In a developing country, talking about the environment is often seen as an unconscionable luxury", says Ganga Voice activist Malika Bhanot.
The court is trying to find a balance between ecology and development".
