Xi Jinping calls for more open economy
The economy needs to be more open to the world to boost growth, President Xi Jinping said Tuesday in an address to a group tasked with leading reforms.
"China should concentrate on attracting foreign investors and experts and develop an open-door policy", he said, addressing the participants of the 16th meeting of the Committee of the central lead group on comprehensive deepening of reforms.
He said expanding openness and deepening reforms would give the economy new impetus and vitality and provide new space for economic development.
The group adopted a number of directives, including regulating investor access to markets, changing border control rules, encouraging state-owned enterprises (SOEs) to attract private capital and revising the resident registration system.
According to the statement, a list of economic and production sectors that are not available for investment will be drawn up.
The system will be gradually debugged through trial programs.
This is an important step as it will give the market a more significant role in allocating resources, ensuring business legitimacy and increasing transparency, the statement said.
The government will also loosen the control of the powers it gives to companies, thereby ensuring that companies will run their own businesses.
The statement also said that China will allow border regions to learn new models of cross-border economic cooperation and new mechanisms to enhance local growth.
More spheres will be open to private investors in order to increase the openness of state-controlled sectors of the economy.
"The government will not change its policy towards foreign investors and will protect the legitimate interests of foreign-funded companies and provide them with the best conditions", the statement said.
